==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fell
<hw>Fell</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>fel</ets>, OF.
<ets>fel</ets> cruel, fierce, perfidious; cf. AS. <ets>fel</ets> (only
in comp.) OF. <ets>fel</ets>, as a noun also accus. <ets>felon</ets>, is
fr. LL. <ets>felo</ets>, of unknown origin; cf. Arm <ets>fall</ets>
evil, Ir. <ets>feal</ets>, Arm. <ets>falloni</ets> treachery, Ir. &
Gael. <ets>feall</ets> to betray; or cf. OHG. <ets>fillan</ets> to flay,
torment, akin to E. <ets>fell</ets> skin. Cf. <er>Felon</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Cruel; barbarous; inhuman; fierce; savage;
ravenous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While we devise <qex>fell</qex> tortures for thy faults.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Eager; earnest; intent.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am so <qex>fell</qex> to my business.</q>
<rj><qau>Pepys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fell
<hw>Fell</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>fel</ets> gall, bile, or
E. <ets>fell</ets>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>Gall; anger;
melancholy.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Untroubled of vile fear or bitter <qex>fell</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fell
<hw>Fell</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>fell</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>vel</ets>, OHG. <ets>fel</ets>, G. <ets>fell</ets>, Icel.
<ets>fell</ets> (in comp.), Goth <ets>fill</ets> in
⟦thorn⟧ruts<ets>fill</ets> leprosy, L. <ets>pellis</ets> skin, Gr.
<grk>pe`lla</grk>. Cf. <er>Film</er>, <er>Peel</er>, <er>Pell</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>A skin or hide of a beast with the wool or
hair on; a pelt; -- used chiefly in composition, as
wool<xex>fell</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We are still handling our ewes, and their <qex>fells</qex>, you
know, are greasy.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Fell
<hw>Fell</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>fell</ets>,
<ets>fjally</ets>; akin to Sw. <ets>fj⟦aum⟧ll</ets> a ridge or chain of
mountains, Dan. <ets>fjeld</ets> mountain, rock and prob. to G.
<ets>fels</ets> rock, or perh. to <ets>feld</ets> field, E.
<ets>field</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A barren or rocky hill.</def>
<rj><au>T. Gray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A wild field; a moor.</def>
<rj><au>Dryton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Fell
<hw>Fell</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Felled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Felling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>fellan</ets>, a
causative verb fr. <ets>feallan</ets> to fall; akin to D.
<ets>vellen</ets>, G. <ets>f⟦aum⟧llen</ets>, Icel. <ets>fella</ets>, Sw.
<ets>f⟦aum⟧lla</ets>, Dan. <ets>f⟦ae⟧lde</ets>. See <er>Fall</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <def>To cause to fall; to prostrate; to bring
down or to the ground; to cut down.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stand, or I'll <qex>fell</qex> thee down.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Fell
<hw>Fell</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>The finer portions
of ore which go through the meshes, when the ore is sorted by
sifting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 8 ====
HEADWORD: Fell
<hw>Fell</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Gael. <ets>fill</ets> to fold,
plait, Sw. <ets>f⟦aring⟧ll</ets> a hem.]</ety> <def>To sew or hem; --
said of seams.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 9 ====
HEADWORD: Fell
<hw>Fell</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Sewing)</fld> <def>A form
of seam joining two pieces of cloth, the edges being folded together and
the stitches taken through both thicknesses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Weaving)</fld> <def>The end of a web, formed by the
last thread of the weft.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fellable</ent>⟦br⟧
